<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910325-0048</DOCNO><DOCID>910325-0048.</DOCID><HL>   Hughes Unit Sues Government</HL><DATE>03/25/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B2</SO><CO>   GM GMH</CO><IN>AEROSPACE (ARO)</IN><GV>JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (FDL)</GV><LP>   WASHINGTON -- A unit of Hughes Aircraft Co. sued thefederal government over its decision to cancel a contract tolaunch 10 Hughes satellites on the space shuttle. Hughes, aunit of General Motors Corp., seeks $288 million in damages.   The complaint, filed in U.S. Claims Court here, allegesthat Hughes Communications Galaxy suffered &quot;substantialeconomic harm&quot; from the 1986 decision, which came in the wakeof the Challenger shuttle explosion that killed sevenastronauts. After the disaster, President Reagan directed theNational Aeronautics and Space Administration to removeitself from the commercial launch business.</LP><TEXT>   Edward Frankle, NASA's general counsel, said the agencyhadn't studied the complaint closely but said its responseprobably will be &quot;that we don't owe them $288 million.&quot;</TEXT></DOC>